From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] sky2: MDIO address scan diagnostic for Baikal PHY discovery

v68 boot proved the driver binds and registers enp0s20f1, but the PHY
chip is invisible: dmesg shows 8x "phy I/O error" when systemd brings
the interface admin-up, then no further events even when an ethernet
cable is plugged. The wlan still works (so it isn't a kernel hang),
but ethernet has no carrier ever.

Our existing 0001 patch sets `hw->phy_addr = 1` (matching what Aeolia
needs). Empirical result on Baikal: addr 1 doesn't respond. This is
diagnostic: sweep all 32 MDIO addresses (0..31) right after sky2_init
returns, and log every address that returns non-trivial PHY ID
registers. Restores hw->phy_addr to its original value after, so the
rest of probe runs unchanged.

Expected outcomes when the patched kernel boots:

  Case A — some address responds:
      PS4 Baikal: MDIO addr  3 responds: ID0=0x0141 ID1=0x0CC2 ...
      → 0x0141 is Marvell's OUI prefix (PHY_MARV_ID0_VAL), 0x0CC2 is
        Yukon-EC PHY 88E1111. Then v70 hardcodes phy_addr=3 (or
        whatever address).

  Case B — no responses, all 32 addresses silent:
      → The PHY isn't on the MDIO bus at all. Confirms rmuxnet's
        Belize-tree hint that Baikal silicon may have a DWMAC-style
        memory-mapped PHY block instead of a Yukon MDIO bus. Pivots
        the next iteration to RE'ing the DWMAC1000 register layout
        for PHY status access.

Either way, this patch GIVES us the data to choose. After v69 boot,
pull the new "PS4 Baikal: MDIO addr ..." lines and we know the answer.

The patch only runs on PS4 Baikal (gated by vendor+device PCI IDs),
restores hw->phy_addr after the scan, and uses dev_info() — no impact
on Aeolia or Belize behavior, and no runtime cost on non-PS4 boots.
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
@@ -5028,6 +5028,34 @@
 	if (err)
 		goto err_out_iounmap;

+#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
+	if (pdev->vendor == PCI_VENDOR_ID_SONY &&
+	    pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_GBE) {
+		/* Sweep MDIO addresses 0..31 to find where the Baikal PHY
+		 * actually responds. The patch 0001 assumption (addr=1, same
+		 * as Aeolia) appears wrong — sky2_read_phy logs phy I/O errors
+		 * at boot and never sees link. Log every address that returns
+		 * a non-trivial ID register pair so we can pick the right one
+		 * for the next iteration. */
+		unsigned saved = hw->phy_addr;
+		int scan_a;
+		dev_info(&pdev->dev, "PS4 Baikal: MDIO scan starting (addrs 0..31)\n");
+		for (scan_a = 0; scan_a < 32; scan_a++) {
+			u16 id0 = 0xffff, id1 = 0xffff;
+			int e0, e1;
+			hw->phy_addr = scan_a;
+			e0 = __gm_phy_read(hw, 0, PHY_MARV_ID0, &id0);
+			e1 = __gm_phy_read(hw, 0, PHY_MARV_ID1, &id1);
+			if (e0 == 0 && id0 != 0xffff && id0 != 0)
+				dev_info(&pdev->dev,
+					 "PS4 Baikal: MDIO addr %2d responds: ID0=0x%04x ID1=0x%04x (e0=%d e1=%d)\n",
+					 scan_a, id0, id1, e0, e1);
+		}
+		hw->phy_addr = saved;
+		dev_info(&pdev->dev, "PS4 Baikal: MDIO scan complete, phy_addr restored to %u\n", hw->phy_addr);
+	}
+#endif
+
 	/* ring for status responses */
 	hw->st_size = hw->ports * roundup_pow_of_two(3*RX_MAX_PENDING + TX_MAX_PENDING);
 	hw->st_le = dma_alloc_coherent(&pdev->dev,
